```jsx
import React, { createContext, useState } from 'react';

// Create context with a default value (optional)
export const UserContext = createContext(null);

// Create a provider component
export const UserProvider = ({ children }) => {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  return (
    <UserContext.Provider value={{ user, setUser }}>
      {children}
    </UserContext.Provider>
  );
};
```

- The `Provider` accepts a `value` prop (any data, often an object with state and updater).
- It must wrap the components that need access.

In your root component (e.g., App.js):

```jsx
import { UserProvider } from './context/UserContext';

export default function App() {
  return (
    <UserProvider>
      <MainApp />
    </UserProvider>
  );
}
```

Now any component inside `MainApp` can access the user context.
